player.seasonOutlook: Winner of the 2017-18 Hart Trophy as the NHL's Most Valuable Player, big things were expected from both Hall and his team last season. Hall ended up missing New Jersey's final 29 games with what the club termed a "lower-body injury". It was later revealed that Hall injured his knee and subsequently underwent surgery, but Hall himself has stated that there was no specific incident that led to the injury. Hall was his typical productive self when he suited up (11 goals, 33 points in 37 games), but the mysterious circumstances surrounding his long-term absence are a concern. Hall is scheduled to become an unrestricted free agent following this coming season and has thus far declined to negotiate a new contract with New Jersey. Hall is a first-round fantasy talent, but there's definitely a risk here.

A finalist for the Norris Trophy as the NHL's top defenseman for the third straight season, Hedman was his usual productive self (12 goals, 54 points) despite missing 12 contests due to injury. He also sat out the final two games of Tampa Bay's sweep at the hands of the Blue Jackets in the first round of the playoffs due to an undisclosed injury. Hedman is expected to be fully healthy for training camp, and as the top defenseman and power-play quarterback for arguably the league's most talented team, it's easy to see why he will be one of the first rearguards off the board in fantasy drafts this coming fall. The big Swede has posted no fewer than 25 points with the man advantage in each of the past three seasons, so give him a bump in leagues that place an extra emphasis on power-play production.

DeBrincat terrorized goalies around the league last season, going off for 41 goals as an NHL sophomore. He became a featured weapon on the Chicago power play (3:16 per game, 13 goals, 24 points), which should continue in 2019-20. While his 18.6 percent shooting percentage is unsustainable, DeBrincat is such a gifted goal scorer that it's reasonable to expect a floor of 30-plus tallies in what will be just his age-22 season. The thought of the Michigan native continuing to fire home one-timers from future Hall of Famer Patrick Kane should entice fantasy owners, as it's one of the main reasons DeBrincat is primed for another big season this fall.

The NHL's ultimate agitator, Marchand has also proven himself to be one of the league's very best offensive weapons. In addition to being just one of six players to finish last season with at least 100 points, the 31-year-old was eighth in the league in assists (64), tied for eighth in power-play points (34) and tied for second in game-winning goals (nine). Marchand battled through a few different injuries in the postseason, but he is expected to be fine for training camp. Playing for one of the best teams in the league and having posted no fewer than 85 points in each of the past three seasons, Marchand is set up for continued long-term success. He is well worth a late first-round selection in redraft leagues this coming fall.

Finally getting the recognition he deserves as one of the NHL's elite two-way pivots, Barkov was named Florida's captain prior to the 2018-19 campaign and responded with career-best marks (35 goals, 61 assists, 96 points, 31 power-play points) across the board. He finished fourth among league forwards in ice time (22:21) and won 53.7 of his faceoffs. Barkov has the quick hands to play a skill game, the size to play a power game, and is the rare offensive player who is a legitimate asset in all three zones. Set to turn 24 years of age in September and signed for the next three seasons to a team-friendly deal that pays him just $5.9 million per season, Barkov isn't even close to a finished product yet, which is a scary thought for the rest of the NHL.

Possibly the NHL's most consistent two-way defenseman, Josi continues to go about his business. The 29-year-old is coming off another stellar season in which he posted 15 goals and 56 points while playing in all 82 games for Nashville. Josi finished fifth in the league in ice time (25:10) and was second in shots on goal by a defenseman with 274, trailing only the 300 posted by San Jose's Brent Burns. Going back to the 2013-14 campaign when he seized a full-time role on the Predators blue line, Josi has posted no fewer than 12 goals, 40 points, and 12 points with the man advantage in the subsequent six seasons. Josi doesn't possess the dynamic qualities of Burns or a guy like Erik Karlsson, but he is likely a better all-around player and an easy choice to anchor of any fantasy squad.

In his rookie season, Pettersson led all first-year players in goals (28), assists (38), points (66), power-play goals (10), power-play points (22) and game-winning goals (7). As such, he was awarded the Calder Trophy, but it's important to note that his 19.4 shooting percentage will almost assuredly drop in his sophomore campaign. He also missed 11 games  -- six of which were concussion-related -- due to injury so owners will be looking for the youngster to prove his durability in Year 2. Still, Vancouver's leading scorer should continue to trend upward as he adjusts his game to the rigors of the NHL, and a full season with linemate Brock Boeser should reap rewards for both players.

Very few players can match the physical gifts of MacKinnon. The 2013 first-overall selection possesses world-class speed, an excellent shot, and fantasy hands. MacKinnon has posted 80 goals and 196 points in his last 156 regular-season games, and it's crazy to think he's only heading into his age-24 season. Colorado is a team on the rise, and MacKinnon is the main reason why. Further solidified as one of the most prolific fantasy weapons in the league thanks to the emergence of fellow superstar linemate Mikko Rantanen (87 points in 74 games last year), the Nova Scotia native should probably be the third forward off the board behind only Connor McDavid and reigning Hart Trophy winner Nikita Kucherov.

There were rumblings that Meier might be a potential target for an offer sheet this summer, but San Jose quickly locked him up to a four-year, $24 million contract extension on July 1. Coming off a season in which he posted 30 goals and 66 points as a 22-year-old, it's easy to see why the Sharks were in a rush to get a deal done. Meier's breakout campaign would have almost certainly been even bigger had he received more than 1:48 worth of average power-play time. With Joe Pavelski off to Dallas and Gustav Nyquist having signed in Columbus, Meier is a lock for increased time with the man advantage in 2019-20. There is legitimate 40-goal upside here and it could manifest itself as early as this coming season. Draft Meier accordingly.

Grubauer supplanted the since-departed Semyon Varlamov as the starter in Colorado late last season, posting a 1.69 GAA and .948 save percentage in 16 regular-season appearances from February onward before adding a 2.30 GAA and .925 save percentage in 12 postseason contests. The German netminder has a stellar 2.39 career GAA and .921 save percentage, but he has never made more than 37 appearances in a season, so Colorado's running some risk in handing him the reins to the starting job. If Grubauer can maintain his level over a full season, he should find plenty of success on a talented Avalanche club.

Arvidsson's 2018-19 campaign was a mixed bag. On the plus side, his 34 markers in 58 games were a career high and placed him among the league-leaders in goals per game. On the other hand, his assist total (14) was way down, his shooting percentage was abnormally high (17.4 percent), and Arvidsson missed nearly two months due to a broken thumb. He's never been a productive player with the man advantage -- his career-high in power-play points in a season is nine, and he had just four last year -- so it's imperative for him to do most of his damage at even strength. The diminutive Swede has proven he can get the job done, but it will almost certainly come with a few less goals and a few more assists than last year.

Nurse is fresh off the most productive season of his four-year career. He set career highs in goals (10), assists (31) and points (41), and finished with nine power-play points after posting just a single assist with the man advantage in his first four seasons combined. That said, a repeat performance appears to be unlikely. 2018 10th-overall selection Evan Bouchard is expected to take over this coming season as the quarterback on Edmonton's power play, and without that extra production with the man advantage, Nurse is just another run-of-the-mill fantasy defender. Nurse will still have value in deeper leagues considering his ice time (23:49 last year) and the fact that lining up alongside Connor McDavid and Leon Draisaitl gets everyone a few extra points, but the odds of Nurse taking another step forward offensively aren't great.

It's difficult to imagine Pavelski in anything other than a teal jersey, but the 35-year-old is off to Dallas, having signed a three-year, $21 million contract following 13 seasons and 963 contests with the Sharks. After posting 29 and 22 goals respectively the previous two seasons, Pavelski bounced back with a 38-goal campaign in 2018-19. That lofty number is likely unsustainable and was the direct result of an inflated 20.2 shooting percentage (the highest of his career), but Pavelski remains one of the NHL's premier net-front powerplay producers and is joining a team with a strong supporting cast featuring Tyler Seguin, Jamie Benn, Alexander Radulov and John Klingberg. While his goal output will probably drop, Pavelski's assist total (26 last season) should rise. All in all, the former San Jose captain should once again be good for 65 points in 2019-20.

Duchene's desire to join the Predators was one of summer's worst kept secrets, as the two agreed to a seven-year, $56 million contract just moments after the opening bell of unrestricted free agency on July 1. He should slot right in as the Preds No. 2 center and add much needed scoring depth to a club that saw its offensive output suddenly vanish in the postseason. Duchene is coming off a season in which he set a career high in goals (31) and tied his career best in points (70). With a secure role on a strong team at age 28, Duchene should be good for at least 25 markers and 60 points in his debut campaign in Smashville. Those kinds of numbers make him a strong fantasy option, albeit not one worth breaking the bank for.

Health will be the key to a strong season for Raanta, as he has never appeared in more than 47 games in a season and was limited to just 12 games in 2018-19 by a lower-body injury. Darcy Kuemper fared well as the starter after Raanta went down last season, so cracking 50 starts won't be easy for the Finnish netminder given his history and the competition in Arizona's net. With a career 2.34 GAA and .920 save percentage, Raanta should fare well on a per-start basis, and Arizona's offseason acquisition of sniper Phil Kessel suggests the team intends to make a strong push for its first playoff berth since 2012.

On the heels of a 2017-18 season which saw him post career highs in goals (35) and points (92) while finishing tied for seventh in league scoring, Kopitar's 2018-19 statistics (22 goals, 60 points) were much more in line with what we have come to expect from the 31-year-old. The Kings played the entire season without a legitimate top-six left-winger to line up alongside Kopitar, and the production of both the aging Dustin Brown on the club's default No. 1 line and Kopitar suffered as a result. Los Angeles is slowly building its prospect pool, but none of the top guys figure to be ready to help the NHL club this coming season. This figures to add up to the Kings once again falling outside the playoff picture in the Western Conference and Kopitar producing 50-55 points.

Aho became the first player since Ryan O'Reilly in 2013 to sign an offer sheet as a restricted free agent. His five-year, $42.27 million agreement with Montreal in July was matched in short order by the Hurricanes, and Carolina now has its unquestioned offensive leader under contract long-term. Aho is fresh off his first 30-goal season that culminated in a whopping 83 points in 82 games, and he just turned just 22 years old, so it's reasonable to believe that he hasn't come close to reaching his ceiling yet. Aho has already proven he has the requisite skill set to be a major point producer at a young age and his numbers should only increase as he matures. Draft him early and with confidence.

The days of grabbing Draisaitl at a potential discount on draft day have come and gone. The big Oilers center is coming off a season in which he joined Alex Ovechkin as the NHL's only 50-goal scorers. Draisaitl's 50 goals were twice as many as the 25 he posted in 2017-18, and his 105 points were 35 more than his previous best. Hitting the half-century mark once again would appear to be unsustainable given the fact he scored 16 times with the man advantage and posted an insane 21.6 percent shooting percentage, but betting against Draisaitl, and by extension, Connor McDavid, is a poor idea. Draisaitl could finish with 10 fewer goals and 15 fewer points than a season ago and still be one of the NHL's very best players.

Like fine wine, Bergeron continues to get better with age. While the future Hall of Famer missed at least 17 games for a second straight season in 2018-19, he somehow managed to put together the best offensive season of his career. His 32 goals tied a career-high mark previously set in 2015-16, and his 79 points (27 with the man advantage) were a new best for the 34-year-old. While Bergeron poses a significant injury risk, his line with Brad Marchand and David Pastrnak has developed into one of the most dominant in the league, which should lead to continued high-end production for the veteran. While he’s still dealing with a lingering groin issue, he is expected to be ready for the season opener after receiving a platelet-rich plasma injection in July.

Auston Matthews and John Tavares may get most of the publicity, but one could argue the 22-year-old Marner is Toronto's most valuable player. He is coming off a season in which he set a new career high in goals (26) and shattered his previous bests in both assists (68) and points (94). Marner is a legitimate all-around offensive threat, and after not missing a game in the past two seasons, he has durability on his side. Few players can match Marner's combination of both ceiling and floor, and as such, should be one of the first forwards off the board, especially now that his contract impasse with the Buds is behind him.

Tkachuk's numbers improved slightly in each of his first two NHL campaigns, but it was his third season in which we saw a significant jump. Now armed with a fresh three-year, $21 million contract extension signed at the end of September, the 2016 first-rounder finished with 28 more points (77) in 2018-19 than a season prior and cracked the 30-goal plateau (34) for the first time in his young career. Additionally, he was more effective with the man advantage (24 points) and finished with a career-high 207 shots on goal. Tkachuk won't turn 22 until December and his breakout appears to be sustainable. Tkachuk may never be the type of player who will lead the NHL in scoring, but 35 goals and 80 points per season for the next half decade appear to be well within reach as part of a potent Flames attack.

Binnington took the league by storm last season, posting a 24-5-1 record, 1.89 GAA and .927 save percentage in the regular season before becoming the first rookie goaltender to win 16 postseason games en route to the Stanley Cup. While he'll almost certainly regress with a larger regular-season sample size, the athletic 26-year-old has plenty of room to drop while still being a valuable fantasy commodity. Given his tremendous results at the NHL level and the wellrounded team in front of him, the question with Binnington isn't whether he'll be good, but rather just how good he'll be after bringing the Blues their first championship in franchise history.

Benn is coming off his worst full-season performance (53 points in 78 games) since his 2009-10 rookie campaign. The sudden drop in production can be contributed to Benn producing just 11 points with the man advantage after finishing with no fewer than 22 power-play points in each of the previous four seasons. His powerplay time dropped slightly (2:38 compared to 3:03 the season prior), but that still doesn't explain the massive shift in production. Given all of Dallas' offensive weapons -- including new additions Joe Pavelski and Corey Perry -- one would think Benn would be a prime rebound candidate. He just turned 30 despite being around for what seems like forever, and he has missed just 10 regular season games in the past six years. If you're looking for an under-the-radar value play who could potentially carry you to a fantasy championship, Benn seems like a viable candidate.

Gibson's likely to be dragged down by the team in front of him -- his .917 save percentage last season tied for 11th among goalies who made at least 33 appearances, but his 2.84 GAA ranked 25th among the same category of netminders. The Ducks also scored a league-low 2.39 goals per game last season, leading Gibson to just 26 wins in 58 starts. Gibson's still one of the league's most talented goaltenders, but his ability is unlikely to shine through on the stat sheet except for save percentage barring an unexpected improvement from the team in front of him.

Guentzel was arguably the league's most unlikely 40-goal scorer last year. The third-year pro reached the milestone mark in Pittsburgh's regular season finale against the Rangers before being atypically quiet (one goal, zero assists) in the Pens four-game first-round sweep at the hands of the Islanders. It was later revealed that Guentzel was playing through a short-term rib injury in the postseason. It may be a stretch for Guentzel to post 40 markers once again this coming season, but keep in mind this is a player who is all but a lock to line up alongside superstar Sidney Crosby once again, in addition to occupying a prominent role on Pittsburgh's top power-play unit. The fact that Guentzel doesn't turn 25 until October make Guentzel a borderline No. 1 winger in fantasy drafts this fall.

Hart is a dynasty-league darling, and there's plenty to like about him in redraft formats, as well. He started 30 games as a 20-year-old last season, posting a 2.83 GAA and .917 save percentage along with 16 wins for a Flyers team that had one of the league's leakiest defenses. Defense should still be an issue for Philadelphia, but Hart has the talent to mask some of those shortcomings in his first full season as a starter. There's certainly some risk here given Hart's inexperience, but the reward could be great if everything clicks for the former WHL Everett Silvertip

Zibanejad's much anticipated breakout finally occurred in 2018-19. He set career-best marks in goals (30), assists (44), points (74), and power-play points (23), and did so with little offensive talent around him for most of the season. With free agent signee Artemi Panarin and top offensive prospects Kaapo Kakko and Vitali Kravtsov set to join the Rangers, Zibanejad will be presented with a golden opportunity to take his game to an even higher level. As the unquestioned top center for one of the league's most promising up-and-coming teams, it's easy to see why Zibanejad is worthy of early attention in fantasy drafts this fall.

Fresh off signing an eight-year, $66 million contract, Ekman-Larsson put together another steady, solid season in 2018-19. His goal (14) and point (44) totals were right in line with his career averages, and his plus/minus rating improved considerably (minus-16) compared to two seasons ago (minus-28). Factoring in Ekman-Larsson's power-play contributions (19 points last season) and physicality (162 hits) makes it easy to see why the big Swede is one of fantasy hockey's most desirable all-around defensive options. Look for more of the same in 2019-20, especially as OEL gets the opportunity to dish to newly acquired sniper Phil Kessel.

The warm weather of South Florida clearly agreed with Hoffman, as his first season with the Panthers resulted in career highs in goals (36), points (70), power-play goals (17), power-play assists (18) and power-play points (35). Hoffman's 17 tallies with the man advantage ranked fourth in the NHL behind only Brayden Point, Steven Stamkos and Alex Ovechkin, and his 35 power-play points ranked sixth. It remains to be seen what Florida's lines will look like this coming season under new head coach Joel Quenneville, but "Coach Q" won't be able to keep Hoffman off the club's No. 1 power-play unit with those kinds of numbers. Hoffman has one year remaining on his contract before he's eligible for unrestricted free agency, so expect the trade rumblings to pick up if the Panthers get off to a slow start this season.

Hoping to build on his career-best 2017-18 campaign in which he posted 34 goals and 69 points, Rakell had his season interrupted in early December when an ankle injury cost him a month and 12 games worth of action. He was ineffective upon returning to the Anaheim lineup before improving considerably (seven goals, 10 points in his final seven games) late in the year. That said, there are reasons for optimism moving forward. For one, Rakell's shooting percentage was an abnormally low 9.3 last year, and it's reasonable to expect that number to rise. Secondly, with veteran Corey Perry's contract bought out by the Ducks this summer, Rakell's role on Anaheim's top line and top power-play unit is secure. Combine all that with a return to full health and you have a solid value play on your hands.

Playing his entire freshman campaign at age 19, Tkachuk was one of the few bright spots for Ottawa last season. He cracked the 20-goal plateau (22), finished second in rookie scoring (45 points) behind Vancouver's Elias Pettersson, and contributed a whopping 174 hits for good measure. Unlike most first-year players, Tkachuk finished his year strong, posting six goals in his final 10 games. Tkachuk will make strides as an individual player in 2019-20, but Ottawa's glaring lack of offensive depth really limits his overall ceiling. It'll take another couple seasons before Tkachuk becomes a top-flight fantasy option, and for now, owners should expect 50-55 points behind 150-200 hits.

Clearly on the decline due to a multitude of injuries, the 34-year-old Getzlaf is coming off his lowest point total (48 in 67 games) since his 2005-06 rookie campaign. He played nearly two minutes less per game (19:28) last season than the previous year (21:26), and his power-play time (2:42) was an all-time low. Getzlaf provides some additional value in leagues that value hits (150 last year), but owners expecting a big-time offensive rebound are likely to be disappointed. Getzlaf can't seem to stay healthy, and Anaheim lacks the personnel to surround him with legitimate offensive weapons.

The Sabres slogged through another mediocre campaign, but Eichel managed to finally put it all together. Healthy for most of the season, Eichel averaged more than a point-per-game in 2018-19 (28 goals, 82 points in 77 games) for the first time in his four-year career. His 26 points with the man advantage were a career best, and his 303 shots on goal ranked fifth in the league. With 40-goal-scorer Jeff Skinner signed to a new eight-year contract and further improvement expected from forward Casey Mittelstadt and 2018 first-overall pick defenseman Rasmus Dahlin, it's easy to envision an increasingly potent Sabres attack. As a result, Eichel's production could take another significant step forward in 2019-20.

After putting up 52, 58 and 58 points in the prior three seasons, Toews went off last year en route to career-best marks in goals (35), assists (46), points (81), shots (235), power-play points (23) and ice time (21:00). The long and the short of it is that Toews's resurgent season presents a conundrum for fantasy owners. On one hand, projecting Toews to match those totals once again seems foolhardy and highly unlikely. On the other, betting against a three-time Stanley Cup champion and unquestioned leader in an offense that features superstar Patrick Kane and 41-goal-scorer Alex DeBrincat seems unwise. Let's split the difference and project Toews for roughly 25 goals and 65 points in 2019-20.

Just when it seemed as if Kane appeared to be on the decline, the 2007 first-overall selection rebounded with the best offensive season of his storied twelve-year career. His 66 assists and 110 points were both career-best marks. Kane has always been a guy who racked up a ton of helpers, but the fact he scored 44 goals last season was the real surprise. He finished tied for second in the league with a whopping 341 shots on goal --- three more than Alex Ovechkin -- after never posting more than 292. Kane is both supremely talented and durable (he's missed one regular-season game in the past four seasons), so he will continue to produce elite numbers, but expecting another 40-plus-goal and 100-plus-point season is probably a mistake given all the things that need to go right to get there.

There's not much to get excited about when looking at Lundqvist's stats from the past two seasons (44-49-17 record, 3.02 GAA and .911 save percentage), but the 37-year-old netminder could have a bounce-back campaign behind a retooled Rangers team. After all, we're talking about a guy who has come up short of 30 wins only three times in 14 seasons while posting a career 2.41 GAA and .918 save percentage. Lundqvist will need to be rested more than some workhorse starters and almost certainly won't crack 60 starts, but he could provide plenty of value if New York makes the jump from rebuilder to contender after adding a star winger (Artemi Panarin), first-pairing defenseman (Jacob Trouba) and second-overall pick (Kaapo Kakko) this summer.

Stone began the 2018-19 campaign in Ottawa before being dealt to Vegas at the trade deadline after refusing to sign a new contract with the Sens. He immediately inked an eight-year, $76 million deal with Vegas and played well late in the season (five goals, 11 points in 18 games) before going nuts (six goals, 12 points) in a seven-game first-round playoff loss to San Jose. Stone has long been one of the NHL's most underrated players. He's nothing more than an average skater, but his shot and hockey sense are phenomenal, who's more than capable of leading the man advantage. Vegas, given its offensive depth, was one of the best possible landing spots for Stone in terms of fantasy value, and the 27-year-old should be good for about a point-per-game in 2019-20.

Fleury is the only starting goaltender the Golden Knights have ever known, and they've been spoiled with two years of excellence, as the former Penguin has posted a 64-34-9 record, 2.40 GAA and .919 save percentage since coming over to Vegas in the expansion draft. He turns 35 in November, but Fleury looks like he still has some high quality campaigns in him behind what once again projects to be one of the better teams in the league. Fleury has won at least 34 games nine times in his career, and he's well positioned to hit double digits this season given his situation.

Kane is coming off a respectable season for the Sharks (30 goals, 56 points in 75 games), but the club will almost certainly be expecting more after handing him a seven-year, $49 million contract in the spring of 2018. The good news is that Kane is almost always among the league-leaders in shots on goal, so perhaps his much-anticipated breakout is on the way. Kane averaged just 1:55 worth of man-advantage time in 2018-19 (11 points), but the departure of long-time San Jose captain Joe Pavelski to Dallas should result in Kane seeing a bump in that area. Kane's floor is high -- he's scored no fewer than 28 goals in each of the past three seasons -- but looking for 70-plus points from him at this point is probably misguided.

With Nashville looking to clear cap space to make a multitude of roster moves, Subban was the player it deemed expendable. The Predators reportedly had conversations with a handful or teams about P.K., but New Jersey was the only club willing to take on the entirety of the remaining three years ($9 million cap hit) of Subban's contract. The Devils certainly have their flaws, but they also can run Subban, former league MVP Taylor Hall, sniper Kyle Palmieri, former KHL MVP Nikita Gusev and 2019 first-overall pick Jack Hughes out on their number-one power-play unit. That combination should be one of the very best in the league, and given the fact Subban is certain to log more important minutes for New Jersey than he did for a deep Nashville squad, his fantasy arrow is pointing up as we head into the 2019-20 season.

There appeared to be a point in late June and early July that Lee, the captain of the Islanders, would be leaving town as an unrestricted free agent. Once Artemi Panarin elected to join the rival Rangers instead of the Isles, GM Lou Lamoriello pivoted back to Lee and the two agreed on a new seven-year, $49 million contract. It's a reasonable deal for a player who has scored no fewer than 28 goals in each of the past three seasons. Lee's assist totals (his 23 in 2018-19 were a career high) are always low, and that limits his overall fantasy value, but he should be a lock for 25 tallies in addition to his production with the man advantage. Give the 29-year-old a boost in leagues that place an extra emphasis on goals.

Schenn's drop in production (17 goals, 54 points in 72 games) compared to two seasons ago (28 goals, 70 points in 82 games) was due to a combination of a pair of upper-body injuries that cost the 27-year-old a combined 10 games and skating 48 seconds less on the power play (2:24) compared to 2017-18. The Blues, under new head coach Craig Berube, gained the reputation of being a hardworking team that rolls four lines. Schenn is locked into a top-line role with the club, but he's going to have a difficult time reaching the 70-point plateau once again unless his playing time with the man advantage increases. Schenn, who is scheduled to become an unrestricted free agent in the summer of 2020, should be fully motivated as he enters a contract year.

Ekblad has finished somewhere between 36-39 points in each of the past four seasons in which he has played a minimum of 78 games. While virtually everyone on the Florida roster saw their point totals skyrocket last season, Ekblad's remained steady due to the fact he averaged nearly 30 seconds less with the man advantage (1:42) compared to the year prior. Overall, Ekblad's ice time (23:39) was a new career high, and the Panthers' high-powered offense should once again result in Ekblad maintaining fantasy relevancy. However, don't pay for a breakout that is unlikely to materialize.

The move to Vegas has done wonders for Smith, as the 28-year-old has firmly established himself as a solid top-six contributor for the Golden Knights. Smith's numbers last season (19 goals, 53 points, 14 power-play points, 178 shots on goal) provide a nice baseline for what to expect moving forward. He has fit in exceptionally well alongside William Karlsson and Jonathan Marchessault since touching down in Sin City, and there's no reason for Vegas head coach Gerard Gallant to fix what isn't broken.

Nugent-Hopkins has not only settled into his role as an above-average NHL player, but he is coming off the best season (28 goals, 69 points) of his eight-year career. He will probably never produce enough offensively to make him worthy of the first-overall selection the Oilers spent on him in the 2011, but he's a solid scorer nonetheless. That said, RNH is the clear-cut No. 3 offensive option on a team with Connor McDavid and Leon Draisaitl. That raises Nugent-Hopkins' floor, particularly with the man advantage, but lowers his ceiling since he rarely plays with either of the aforementioned pair of studs at even strength. Perhaps that will change under new head coach Dave Tippett, but Edmonton simply doesn't have the horses to play its top dogs together every night. As a result, it's difficult to see RNH getting over the 70-point plateau at this stage in his career.

Nelson, who would have been eligible for unrestricted free agency last July, picked a good time to have the best all-around season (25 goals, 53 points in 82 games) of his six-year career. The soon-to-be 28-year-old played in all 82 contests for the third time in the past five seasons (he missed just one game in each of the other two) and chipped in eight points with the man advantage for a second straight year. He was rewarded with a new six-year, $36 million contract in May and is set to begin the season as New York's No. 2 center behind Mathew Barzal. Nelson was especially popular with new head coach Barry Trotz, as he saw his ice time rise by more than three minutes on average (17:58).

Greiss had the worst season of his career in 2017-18, then bounced back with his best year last season. After posting an abhorrent 3.82 GAA and .892 save percentage in 27 games two years ago, the German netminder made a complete 180 with a 2.28 GAA and .927 save percentage over 43 games in 2018-19. That improvement can be traced to the hiring of coach Barry Trotz, who instituted an effective defensive system on an Islanders team that previously looked like a bunch of chickens skating around with their heads cut off. Greiss split time with Vezina Trophy finalist Robin Lehner last season and should see a similar split with Lehner's replacement Semyon Varlamov, but the key to his success will be New York's ability to repeat its defensive prowess from a year ago.

The NHL's reigning "Ironman," Yandle is coming off a career year in his age-32 season. The American rearguard finished the 2018-19 campaign with 62 points, including 39 points with the man advantage, making Yandle the first defenseman in the league to post 35 power-play points in a single season since Detroit's Nicklas Lidstrom accomplished the feat back in 2010-11. Yandle's plus/minus was predictably dreadful (minus-17) given the fact his team failed to make the playoffs and received mostly poor goaltending, but fantasy owners aren't inserting Yandle into their lineup for defensive statistics. Florida has about as much high-end offensive depth as any team in the league, and that combined with Yandle's durability make him a strong bet to duplicate his numbers from a season ago.

The Senators are one of the weakest teams in the league, but they boast one of the NHL's premier young defenders in Chabot. After showing signs of life late in the 2017-18 campaign, Chabot took a massive step forward last season to the tune of 14 goals and 55 points in 71 games. He contributed 16 points with the man advantage and averaged a whopping 24:17 worth of ice time. Chabot, at age 22, has his best hockey ahead of him, but keep in mind that his offensive production is going to come with the baggage of a poor plus/minus rating. With that in mind, knock Chabot down a peg or two if your league values that stat.

A third-round pick of the Lightning in 2014, Point has quickly developed into a legitimate superstar. Point set career highs across the board in 2018-19 (41 goals, 51 assists, 91 points, plus-27) along with leading the NHL in power-play goals with 20. And while Point's 21.5 shooting percentage is almost certain to dip a bit, he should still be good for 35-plus tallies in Tampa's high-powered offense. The immediate downside here is that he quietly underwent offseason hip surgery and will miss up to 10 games to start the season. Still just 23 years of age with a fresh three-year contract  with a secure role on one of the league's very best teams, Point is well worth an early investment.

After posting 36 and 44 goals respectively in each of his first two NHL campaigns, Laine came crashing back to earth in 2018-19. He finished with just 30 markers, and that number would have looked significantly worse had he not posted a five-goal game against the Blues in November. From New Year's Eve to mid-February, Laine scored just one goal in 22 games. While Laine's production with the man advantage (15 goals) remained steady, that means he scored just 15 goals in 82 games at even strength.  
 Worse yet is that he’s still without a contract and is training away from the team in Europe as of a week before the season. He's an elite sniper but not a great all-around player, and while a bounce-back could well be in the cards for the 21-year-old, owners seeking a high point total or placing an emphasis on assists should explore other options.

Still without a contract less than a week from the start of the 2019-20 season, Rantanen’s murky status heading into opening night should weigh heavy on fantasy owners. That said, Rantanen has posted a whopping 28 power-play goals and 68 power-play points over the past two seasons. He suffered a fractured leg in Colorado's second-round postseason setback to San Jose but was able to play through the injury and is expected to be fully healthy for training camp in September. Set to turn just 23 in October and having posted no less than 29 goals and 84 points in back-to-back campaigns, Rantanen is primed for continued success next to superstar Nathan MacKinnon and captain Gabriel Landeskog in Denver ... but not until his contract is resolved.

No. 87 reached the century mark in points last season (100) for the first time since 2013-14. The crazy thing is that Crosby's sudden jump in production (he had 89 points in each of the two previous seasons) came in a year in which he finished with 11 fewer power-play points (29) than in 2017-18. All in all, Crosby's numbers have remained remarkably steady the past six seasons. One of the most consistent players in NHL history, Crosby is seemingly a lock once again to finish with 30-plus goals, 50-plus assists, and 220-plus shots on goal while playing well north of 20 minutes nightly. Some may point to the departure of sniper Phil Kessel as a potential cause for concern, but Crosby rarely played with Kessel at even strength, and newcomer Alex Galchenyuk will provide Crosby a solid dishing option on the power play in Kessel's stead.

Due to an abnormally low shooting percentage, Hamilton began his season with just three goals in his first 38 games. He started to find twine with more regularity once the calendar flipped to January, though, and the first-year Hurricane finished with a career-high 18 tallies. He also chipped in 21 assists for good measure. Hamilton's power-play ice time time (1:52) and production (seven points) were both down considerably compared to his final seasons in Calgary, but the rest of his numbers were roughly in line with what we have come to expect from the 26-year-old. Hamilton's floor is enhanced by the fact he is usually among the league's shot leaders from the blue line: his 259 in 2018-19 ranked third behind only San Jose's Brent Burns and Nashville's Roman Josi. Hamilton should easily eclipse the 40-point mark in 2019-20.

With their self-imposed rebuild picking up steam, the Rangers went out and signed Panarin to a seven-year, $81.5 million contract on July 1. The Rangers were able to beat out both the rival Islanders and the Panthers for his services despite the later offering quite a bit more money per season. Since entering the league in 2015-16, Panarin's 320 points put him eighth in the NHL behind only Patrick Kane, Nikita Kucherov, Connor McDavid, Sidney Crosby, Blake Wheeler, Brad Marchand, and Johnny Gaudreau. An elite offensive weapon in every respect, Panarin will be the go-to scoring option for a much-improved Rangers club. He has missed just six regular season games over the course of his first four NHL seasons and won't turn 28 until the end of October. The "Breadman" should once again be good for a point per game in his new digs this year.

Andersen has been remarkably consistent, posting a save percentage between .917 and .919 in each of the past four seasons. The last three of those campaigns have come with Toronto, where Andersen twice started 66 games before dropping down to 60 starts in 2018-19. While the Danish netminder won't challenge for the league lead in GAA, his heavy workload behind a high-scoring offense should help Andersen rack up plenty of wins -- he's averaged 35.7 over the last three seasons.

Tervainen's production has increased in each of his first four full NHL seasons, and his 76 points in 2018-19 (on the strength of 55 assists) made for his most impressive campaign to date. While there's no reason to believe Teravainen will suddenly stop racking up the assists, the fact he rarely shoots the puck is a cause for concern. Teravainen finished last season tied for 144th in the league in shots on goal with 167, which was in line with his total from each of the prior three seasons. At that rate, the 24-year-old Finn will have difficulty scoring more than 20-25 goals a year, and fantasy owners expecting him to significantly increase his point total again in 2019-20 are likely to come away disappointed.

Dumba was off to the best start of his career (12 goals, 22 points, 12 power-play points in 32 games) before suffering a pectoral injury in December that required surgery and cost him the final four months of the season. He is back to full health and expected to be ready to go for training camp. Still just 25 years old and entering the second season of a five-year, $30 million contract he signed in the summer of 2018, Dumba is arguably Minnesota's most important asset. His role on the top power-play unit is secure, and 50 points appears to be well within reach. If Dumba tumbles in fantasy drafts because of last season's injury, owners need to pounce.

A heated contract dispute with Toronto management led to an extended holdout and cost Nylander the first 28 games of the season. He finally signed six-year, $41.4 million deal on Dec. 1 and was in the Leafs lineup four days later, but Nylander struggled due to the missed reps of training camp, finishing the year with just seven goals and 27 points in 54 games. Two particularly rough stretches include one goal in his first 23 games and two in his final 12. It goes without saying that both the team and player need to get this corrected, and given Nylander's skill level, there's no reason he shouldn't find his way back to producing 60-plus points. Nylander can play center and the wing, but the trade of Nazem Kadri to Colorado makes it likely he will begin this coming year up the middle.

With the drafting of Jack Hughes, the acquisitions of P.K. Subban and Nikita Gusev, and the return to full health of Taylor Hall, Hischier has become somewhat of a forgotten commodity in New Jersey, and hopefully fantasy owners can capitalize on that. Nico's numbers last season (17 goals, 47 points) were worse than his 2017-18 rookie campaign (20 goals, 52 points), but he missed 13 games due to injury. If Hischier can make it through this season healthy, he would appear to be a lock to set career highs offensively. The Devils possess far more depth than at any point in the Swiss native's brief NHL run, and his role as both a top-six pivot and power-play member appear secure.

Boeser's numbers last season (26 goals, 56 points) were right in line with his impressive 2017-18 rookie campaign. He was also less effective on the power play (15 points compared to 23 two seasons ago) despite receiving more than 35 seconds (3:32) of additional time with the man advantage. Boeser has been injury-prone in the early portion of his career, as a groin injury cost him 13 games last season after he missed 20 in his debut campaign, and another more immediate concern for owners is the concussion he suffered in a late-September preseason game. 
 Vancouver is trying to ice a more competitive team this year, and that can only be good news for Boeser and his offensive numbers, but he has no shot at a breakout season if he can't remain in the lineup on a consistent basis.

The Sabres remain a work in progress, but Reinhart continues to make strides from an individual perspective. The 2014 second-overall selection has raised his offensive output in each of his first four NHL campaigns, including a career-best 65 points in 2018-19. Reinhart won't wow anyone with his physical gifts, but his hockey sense is exceptional and his role on Buffalo's top line alongside emerging superstar Jack Eichel is secure. Reinhart remains more floor than ceiling, and fantasy owners need to take that into account on draft day, but there is definite value in a guy who should be good for 65-70 points on an improving Sabres squad.

Markstrom should open the year as the starter for an intriguing young Canucks club after winning a career-high 28 games last season while making exactly 60 appearances and posting a .912 save percentage for the second straight campaign. The 6-foot-6 Swede should be serviceable in that role, though it's pretty clear at this point that Markstrom is an average starter at best. He could also spend a lot of time glancing in the rearview mirror, as 2014 second-rounder Thatcher Demko is nearly ready for meaningful NHL time and fits better with the timeline of youngsters like Elias Pettersson and Brock Boeser. Markstrom could push for his first 30-win campaign if he keeps Demko's challenge at bay, but there's a fair amount of risk here for a pretty modest reward.

Fresh off his second season back with the Panthers following a five-year stint in the KHL, Dadonov reaffirmed his status as one of the league's most underrated offensive players. The gifted Russian posted 28 goals for a second straight season in addition to raising his point total from 65 to 70. Dadonov spent nearly the entire season playing alongside stars Aleksander Barkov and Jonathan Huberdeau, and his production would undoubtedly take a hit if he moves to a different line, but Dadonov has shown more than enough the past two seasons to warrant a mid-round fantasy selection.

One of the NHL's most productive offensive rearguards, Krug's scoring rate of 0.82 points per game (53 in 64) was the best of his six-year career. Krug also finished with 30 power-play points, and he would have likely landed among the league leaguers had he not missed the first 11 games of the season due to an ankle injury and six more in March due to a concussion. Entering the final season of a four-year contract that pays him a bargain rate of $5.25 million per season, Krug is eligible for unrestricted free agency on July 1, 2020. Expect the Bruins to do whatever is necessary to lock him up prior to that date, and look for Krug to once again be one of the top fantasy blueliners in his contract year.

The new face of American hockey, Matthews almost certainly would have topped the 40-goal mark for the second time had a shoulder injury suffered in late October against Winnipeg not cost him 14 games. Instead, he finished the season with 37 goals and a career-high 73 points in 68 contests. Matthews' minus-9 rating was disappointing given the fact he plays for such a good team, but he was fantasy gold in every other offensive category. Matthews is an easy point-per-game talent and we sometimes forget this is a kid who will play this entire coming season at just 22 years of age. A massive offensive breakout is forthcoming, and it could very easily happen as soon as this coming year, making Matthews worthy of the high price he will cost come draft day.

After openly stating that he lost his passion for the game while playing for the Sabres, O'Reilly clearly enjoyed playing in St. Louis. After an impressive regular season run (28 goals, 77 points in 82 games), O'Reilly took his game to a new level in the postseason. He was awarded the Conn Smythe Trophy as NHL playoff MVP after posting 23 points in 26 games to help the Blues to their first Stanley Cup Championship. He also took home the Selke Trophy as the NHL's top defensive forward. In addition to his scoring prowess, O'Reilly finished with a plus-22 rating to go along with his usual dominance (56.9 percent) in the faceoff circle. If your fantasy league is one that values plus/minus and faceoff percentage, O'Reilly is one of the very best players in the NHL to have. And if not, he's still a fantastic near-point-per-game asset worth coveting.

Those expecting Ovechkin to suddenly hit a wall in his age-33 season came away sorely disappointed, as he posted 51 goals to earn his eighth Maurice "Rocket" Richard Trophy as the league's top goal-scorer. Ovechkin also finished third in the NHL with 338 shots on goal and added 28 power-play points for good measure. Outside of the 2016-17 campaign in which he had an abnormally low shooting percentage, Ovechkin has finished with at least 49 goals in the other previous six seasons. The Russian power forward should be good for at least 40 goals for another handful of years, and if your league places extra emphasis on hits, no player in the league can match the combination Ovechkin brings to the table after he finished 16th with 223 last year.

2018-19 was one of the least productive offensive seasons (41 points in 71 games) of Pietrangelo's NHL career. The 29-year-old exploded in the postseason to the tune of three goals and 19 points in 26 games and looked stronger as the playoffs culminated with St. Louis' first Stanley Cup. One of the reasons Pietrangelo's regular season production dipped was because he averaged nearly two minutes less (24:05) than the year prior (25:44). Pietrangelo is locked in as the quarterback of St. Louis' No. 1 power-play unit, but the club made a concerted effort to get youngster Vince Dunn time with the man advantage last season, and hard-shooting blueliner Colton Parayko will also be a factor. Pietrangelo remains one of the league's elite two-way defenders, but expectations need to be kept in check fantasy-wise heading into 2019-20.

Having quickly and deservedly gained the reputation of being one of the NHL's most consistent offensive performers, Marchessault is coming off a season in which he reached the 25-goal (25) and 50-point (59) plateaus for a third straight year. He chipped in 16 power-play points, 98 hits, and a career-best 278 shots on goal while playing in all 82 games for the first time in his career. Marchessault remains more floor than ceiling, but there is definite fantasy value in a player who is a lock, health permitting, to post mid-round offensive numbers. Mark Marchessault down for at least 25 goals and 50 points this coming season and go about your day.

Hellebuyck took a step back last season with a 2.90 GAA and .913 save percentage, but he still managed to win 34 games for a talented Jets team. A repeat of 2018-19 would make Hellebuyck a useful fantasy asset, but the 26-year-old netminder's ceiling is much higher than that considering he posted 44 wins with a 2.36 GAA and .924 save percentage in 2017-18. He's locked into one of the league's most desirable starting jobs and is in no danger of age-related decline, so there's little not to like about Hellebuyck.

Traded to Calgary in the deal that sent defenseman Dougie Hamilton to Carolina last summer, Lindholm came out of nowhere to become one of the NHL's most productive scorers in 2018-19. Entering the year having never posted more than 45 points, Lindholm's 78-point explosion gave him more than: Evgeni Malkin, Evgeni Kuznetsov, Mark Stone, Auston Matthews, and Nicklas Backstrom, just to name a few. The Swede spent most of the season alongside Johnny Gaudreau and Sean Monahan before bouncing around later in the year. Lindholm's 14.8 percent shooting percentage is most likely unsustainable, but even a slight dip in production would result in 20-plus goals and 65-plus points for the 24-year-old given the fact he averaged 3:12 worth of power-play time and figures to maintain his hefty role with the man advantage.

Pulock is coming off a season in which he played all 82 games for the first time and set a career high in points with 37. His goal total dropped from 10 to nine, but the main issue for Pulock moving forward is that he's seemingly lost his spot on New York's top power-play unit to fellow defenseman Devon Toews. The Islanders are not a particularly deep team, and the difference in talent between their two power-play units is substantial. Pulock's overall ice time and his willingness to shoot the puck (180 shots on goal last season) make him a worthy fantasy option, but he's more of a mid-tier guy than a potential breakout top-flight option.

Konecny started (five points in his first 13 games) and finished (three in his final 10) his season slowly, but he was an effective player throughout the middle part of the year. When all was said and done, his final numbers (24 goals, 49 points in 82 games) were virtually identical (24 goals, 47 points in 81 games) to his statistics from 2017-18. Konecny should once again fill a top-six role for the Flyers this coming season, but he doesn't project as a breakout candidate if he's only averaging 1:37 worth of power-play time like last year. Philly's addition of Kevin Hayes in free agency further complicated its man advantage personnel configurations, so it'd be wise to tread lightly with Konecny when populating your fantasy squad.

Drafted 20th overall by Chicago in 2014, Schmaltz appeared to be approaching his lofty expectations with a 21-goal, 52-point showing with the Blackhawks in 2017-18. Injuries limited him to just 25 points in 40 games in a season which featured a November trade to Arizona (for Dylan Strome and Brendan Perlini) but his 82-game scoring pace (0.63 points per contest) would have gotten him back over the 50-point plateau. A career-high average power-play time of 3:34 in 17 games with the Coyotes suggests they're comfortable relying on him for production, and an assignment with either Clayton Keller or newly acquired star Phil Kessel should certainly help Schmaltz get on the scoresheet more often. Provided he's fully recovered from January knee surgery, look for another trip to 50-point land, with the potential for even more if he clicks with Kessel.

To give you an idea of how good Schwartz was in St. Louis' run to the Stanley Cup, he posted 12 goals in 26 postseason contests, compared to just 11 goals in 69 regular-season games. Of course, that playoff run will be of no solace to fantasy owners who spent a high draft pick on Schwartz last fall. Schwartz's talent is undeniable, but he has been an injured and inconsistent player for a good portion of his six full seasons in the league. There's reasons to be optimistic moving forward given his playoff performance, but the truth of the matter is that Schwartz is a high-end dice roll until we see him put together back-to-back stellar campaigns.

Parise is coming off a campaign in which he played 74 games for the first time since 2014-15, and his production followed suit with his heatlh. Owners who were able to grab Parise at a discount in their draft last year were rewarded with a 28-goal, 61-point season. Parise has proven he can still contribute at a high level when healthy, but it's anyone guess as to how many games he'll play on a year-to-year basis, but he's near impossible to trust given how much time he has missed in recent years. Owners should be looking at the 35-year-old as a high-end dart throw and nothing more since counting on Parise for any significant production is a recipe for disaster.

The move from Arizona to Montreal clearly agreed with Domi, as the 24-year-old posted career-high numbers (28 goals, 44 assists, 72 points) across the board in his first season with the Habs. His ice time (17:23) increased substantially and he chipped in 80 PIM for good measure. Betting on 70-plus points from Domi once again is a risky proposition considering he managed just 83 the previous two seasons combined, but his role as one of Montreal's top pivots is secure, and his ability to play the wing in a pinch only adds to his floor. Don't overpay for Domi on draft night, but he once again should be a nice source of secondary scoring for fantasy owners.

Bobrovsky might be the best goalie in the NHL, but that doesn't necessarily make him the best fantasy goaltender. The two-time Vezina Trophy winner has a career 2.46 GAA and .919 save percentage, but he underperformed both numbers last year with 2.58 and .913 marks before bolting from Columbus in free agency in favor of Florida's sunny weather and lack of income tax. On one hand, the Panthers figure to provide even more goal support for a guy who has already averaged 38.3 wins over the past three seasons. On the other, Florida gave up the fourth most goals in the league last year. How much of that fell on the shoulders of the team's poor goaltending versus how much had to do with poor defensive play will likely determine whether Bobrovsky finds himself among the elite tier of goaltenders next year.

A knee injury cost Jones the first seven games of the 2018-19 season, but once he returned, he again showed why he is one of the NHL's most dominant two-way defensemen. Jones produces offensively (nine goals, 46 points in 75 games), runs the power play (10 assists), is an asset in leagues that value hits (106) and blocks (133), and does all that while averaging a whopping 25:49 of ice time. Set to turn just 25 years old in early October, Jones is the NHL's most difficult commodity to find: a legitimate No. 1 defenseman who can control the game in all three zones. Jones should be one of the top defensemen selected in fantasy drafts this fall.

The NHL's most dangerous and unstoppable offensive weapon, McDavid continues to outdo himself. Last season, he set career highs in points (116) and power-play points (33) and tied a career-best mark with 41 goals. McDavid has finished in the top five in Hart Trophy voting for a third straight season.  His knee injury in the season finale against Calgary sent shockwaves through the hockey world, but McDavid finally suited up for a preseason game on Sept. 24 and it seems his availability for the start of the 2019-20 campaign is no longer in question. If he’s indeed good to go with no setbacks for opening night, he's a no-brainer top-3 pick.

A serviceable and productive player throughout the first six seasons of his NHL career, Huberdeau finally put together the breakout campaign many thought possible in 2018-19. He set career highs in both goals (30) and points (92) while playing in all 82 games for the second straight season. Huberdeau also picked up 34 points with the man advantage after managing just 39 power-play points over the previous three seasons combined. The best news for fantasy owners is that Huberdeau's sudden increase in production appears to be sustainable given that his shooting percentage (13.3 percent) and ice time (18:51) were roughly in line with his career averages. With Huberdeau slated to once again flank 96-point-man Aleksander Barkov on Florida's top line, the-26-year old should be in line for another big season in Sunrise.

Having made it abundantly clear he would not sign a long-term deal with the Jets, Trouba was dealt to New York in June for the low price of Neal Pionk and the 20th overall pick in the 2019 draft. Trouba signed a brand new seven-year, $56 million deal with the Rangers shortly thereafter to serve as the club's No. 1 defenseman. Trouba is coming off by far the best season of his career. He set high-water marks in assists (42), points (50), and power-play points (18). All those numbers should be in reach for Trouba once again given the massive amount of playing time he is expected to receive in New York. The 25-year-old isn't a top-tier fantasy talent, but he will have the opportunity to produce like one for the next several years.

Following a 2017-18 campaign in which he posted a career-high 60 points to go along with a sparkling plus-23 rating, Doughty's production dried up last season. While his 45 points appear respectable enough on the surface, that scoring came with a horrific minus-34 rating anchored to it. He took 51 less shots last year (154), as well, and ended up with 15 less points despite the fact he upped his power-play point total from 20 to 24. Doughty shouldn't be running out of gas at age 29, but the Kings are an aging hockey club who failed to make any significant improvements this offseason. Doughty has durability on his side, as he hasn't missed a regular season game in five seasons, but fantasy owners would be wise to temper their expectations this coming year.

The 2018-19 campaign was another productive one (72 points in 76 games) for Kuznetsov, but it was a far cry from the 83 points he posted two seasons ago. He started off hot before an upper-body injury suffered in mid-November cost Kuznetsov six games and slowed his production the rest of the way. It was a disappointment for fantasy owners that spent a high pick on the Russian, but there are plenty of reasons to believe that breakout we all expected last season will indeed occur this time around. Kuznetsov is still just 27 and has a secure top-line role on one of the NHL's most talented offensive clubs. He's a lock to produce, particularly on the power play (23 points there last season), and Kuznetsov is safe to target as a No. 1 fantasy center.

Backstrom remains one of the league's better playmakers and power-play specialists, but the days of posting 60-plus assists have seemingly come and gone. Backstrom's 52 helpers in 2017-18 ranked 26th in the NHL (with Toronto defenseman Morgan Rielly), and with Backstrom averaging right around 20 goals per season for the past six years, it will be difficult for him to once again reach the 80-point mark for a fourth time. The 31-year-old Swede makes for a nice secondary scoring option for both the Caps and your fantasy team given the fact he has posted no fewer than 70 points in each of the past six seasons, but Backstrom isn't the difference-maker he once was earlier in his career.

Wilson was handed a 20-game suspension for an illegal hit in the 2018 preseason before it was eventually reduced by to 14 games. He returned to the Washington lineup in mid-November and proceeded to post career highs offensively (22 goals, 40 points) despite playing in just 63 games. He also finished with 100-plus PIM (128) and 200-plus hits (200) for the fifth straight year. Wilson is a useful player when he's focused, but fantasy owners need to keep in mind that one more reckless play could cost the 25-year-old upwards of a quarter of the season or more as a repeat offender.

Trocheck finished the year with 10 goals and 34 points in 55 contests after a grotesque leg injury suffered in mid-November against Ottawa cost him nearly two months worth of action. It's a minor miracle he returned so quickly considering how serious it seemed at the time, and even though he struggled to produce the rest of the way, the fact he was able to suit up at all should be viewed as a positive moving forward. Assuming he is fully healed from the injury, Trocheck should reach the 50-point mark this year without breaking a sweat, as he always contributes with the man advantage and fires a ton of shots on net. Fantasy owners should be prepared to pounce in the event Trocheck unexpectedly slips in drafts this fall.

Having never posted more than 22 goals and 46 points in a season heading into the 2018-19 campaign, few saw Hertl's 35-goal and 74-point explosion coming. Hopefully you had Hertl on your team last year, because his career season was driven by an unsustainable 19.9 shooting percentage. Of all NHL players who played at least 57 games last season, only six (Ivan Barbashev, Valtteri Filppula, Leon Draisaitl, Brayden Point, Joe Pavelski, David Perron) had a higher shooting percentage than Hertl. This isn't to say Hertl's production will drop off the map: he's on a good team, should take on an increased role with the departure of Pavelski and doesn't turn 26 until November, but fantasy owners expecting 35-plus goals once again are likely in for a rude awakening.

Tatar has seemingly risen from the dead. Following a 2017-18 campaign in which he split time between Detroit and Vegas while managing just 20 goals and 34 points, Vegas had seen enough and sent Tatar to Montreal in the Max Paciorretty deal. With the Habs, Tatar reached the 25-goal plateau for the third time and posted career highs in both points (58) and plus/minus (plus-21). Tatar secured a feature role on the Montreal power-play (2:16) and was one again exceedingly durable, as he's missed just three regular-season games over the past five seasons. Fantasy owners should plan for a bit of regression (just to be safe), but Tatar should have no issue landing in 45-55-point territory.

Varlamov's offseason move to the Islanders is intriguing, as New York held opponents to a league-low 2.33 goals per game last season in what was coach Barry Trotz's first year with the team. The Russian netminder has struggled to stay healthy throughout his career, and Thomas Greiss is still on hand after appearing in 43 games and starting 39 last season, so Varlamov's unlikely to finish near the league-leaders in terms of volume. That said, Varlamov's per-game stats could be among the league's best if the Islanders repeat their stellar defensive play from last season, making him a high-risk, high-reward option.

Johansen looked like a future superstar after posting 59 goals during a two-year span (2013-14 to 2014-15) with the Blue Jackets, but his nose for the net has evaporated during his three-plus seasons in Nashville (his goal totals in each of the past four seasons are 14, 14, 15 and 14). He has also played at least 79 games in each of those campaigns, so it's not as if the lack of production is due to extended absences. Johansen continues to rack up the assists (career-high 50 in 2018-19), but his inability to put the puck in the net on a consistent basis limits both his overall ceiling and his value in fantasy circles. Johansen is a useful player, but not one worth overpaying for come draft day.

A broken collarbone suffered in Game 5 of Washington's seven-game Round 1 loss to Carolina put a halt to what was another solid season for Oshie. He reached the 25-goal mark for the third time in the past four years and posted at least 50 points for the fifth time in the past six seasons. Oshie makes for a dicey fantasy proposition moving forward given the fact so much of his production comes with the man advantage (14 points in 2018-19) and the fact he has always been a player with abnormally high shooting percentages (17.5 last year), but the soon to be 33-year-old should be a serviceable middle-round option for another couple seasons.

After a tough year both on and off the ice in Buffalo, Lehner resurrected his career with the Islanders last season, going 25-13-5 with a 2.13 GAA and .930 save percentage. It's worth noting that Thomas Greiss was almost as good after posting a 3.82 GAA in 2017-18, so Lehner's breakout likely had a lot to do with coach Barry Trotz, who was in his first year with New York after leading the Capitals to the Stanley Cup. The Islanders seemed to agree with that sentiment considering they let Lehner walk on a one-year deal to Chicago. If Lehner's 2018-19 was more of his own doing than the conventional wisdom suggests, he'll be a steal at his current valuation. But if he was just a product of a strong system, Lehner's likely in store for an up-and-down campaign splitting time with Corey Crawford behind a questionable defense corps.

Skinner picked a good time to have a career-year. Set to become an unrestricted free agent on July 1, Buffalo resigned Skinner to a new eight-year, $72 million contract. The contract is probably a year or two too long and a million a year too much, but Buffalo really had no choice after Skinner earned his money with a career-best 40 goals and 63 points in 2018-19. Skinner's 14.9 percent shooting percentage will almost certainly drop this coming season, but he should be good for 30-plus goals regardless given all the power-play time (3:05 last year) he receives. He's also durable, having missed just three regular season games in the past four seasons after some concussion concerns earlier in his career. Skinner isn't the type of dominant offensive talent to build your virtual squad around, but he makes for a nice source of secondary scoring in most formats.

Fresh off signing a seven-year, $77 million contract with the Leafs in 2018, Tavares backed up Toronto's faith in him by producing career bests in both goals (47) and points (88) while playing in all 82 games for a second straight season. While Tavares' ice-time with the man advantage (2:36) dropped considerably in his first go-round with the Leafs compared to his final season in New York (3:10 per game), he more than made up for it with increased production at even strength. Toronto's offensive depth allows head coach Mike Babcock to use his multitude of top-six forwards in advantageous situations. This figures to limit Tavares's power-play production moving forward, but it shouldn't have any impact on his overall numbers. 40-plus goals and 80-plus points will once again be well within reach for the soon-to-be 29-year-old.

"Johnny Hockey" has been all the Flames could have hoped for and more when they spent a fourth-round pick on him in 2011, and that trend continued in 2018-19 as Gaudreau posted career-best marks in goals (36), assists (63), points (99), power-play points (27), shots on goal (245) and plus/minus (plus-18). A wizard with the puck and deadly in open ice, Gaudreau is remarkably durable for a guy who is (generously) listed at a diminutive 5-foot-9. Expect another banner year from the 26-year-old New Jersey native given a strong supporting cast (Sean Monahan, Elias Lindholm, Matthew Tkachuk and Mark Giordano all rang up 74 points or more last season) in Cow Town.

Rielly's 2018-19 campaign could not have gone any better. He led all NHL defensemen in goals with 20, and his 72 points shattered his previous career best of 52 set just a season earlier. Rielly also chipped in 21 power-play points while averaging 23:07 worth of ice time. The addition of Tyson Barrie from Colorado should take some pressure of Rielly this coming year, but the 25-year-old will remain the quarterback of the loaded Leafs power-play, and that alone will make Rielly one of fantasy hockey's most valuable defensive commodities.

One of the game's most underrated snipers, Palmieri has posted no fewer than 24 goals in each of his four seasons in New Jersey. He may very well have reached the 30-goal plateau for a second time last year had he not missed eight of the Devils' final 19 games due to injury. Palmieri has never been a picture of health throughout the early portion of his career, and minor issues have seemingly taken longer to heal than originally anticipated. Given his production with the man advantage (no fewer than 18 points the past four years) and additions of 2019 first-overall selection Jack Hughes and dynamic defender P.K. Subban to the New Jersey lineup, the 28-year-old Palmieri projects as a legitimate No. 2 fantasy winger if he can manage to suit up on a nightly basis.

The owner of back-to-back 76-point seasons, the talk of Couturier being a one-hit wonder has rightfully lessened. The 26-year-old potted a career-best 33 goals in 2018-19 in addition to 17 points with the man advantage. Couturier is coming off a year in which he averaged 22:08, a number that placed him sixth among NHL forwards. The Flyers gave Kevin Hayes a monster contract this summer to serve as the club's No. 2 center, but his addition doesn't figure to impact Couturier's production much. It can be difficult to get excited about a player who managed just 70 goals and 191 points in his first 416 NHL games, but Couturier's breakout the past two seasons seems legitimate and likely to continue in 2019-20.

After a down year in 2017-18, Price reestablished himself as one of the top goaltenders in the NHL last season with 35 wins, a 2.49 GAA and .918 save percentage. Those rate stats were right in line with his career 2.47 and .918 marks, but Price's upside is limited by the mediocre Canadiens team in front of him, which had a quiet offseason after missing the playoffs in each of the past two seasons. Still, betting on talent is rarely a poor proposition, and the 2015 Hart Trophy winner has certainly proven that he has that in spades.

A model of consistency, Radulov has put up 72 points in each of the last two seasons and would have likely landed closer to 80 if not for an injury absence. On the power play, the former KHL product put up exactly seven goals and 23 points in back-to-back campaigns, as well. In other words, the Russian forward is a dependable source of near point-per-game scoring and should be regarded highly in the fantasy realm given his top-six role for a Dallas offense bursting with offensive firepower.

Forsberg had a strange season last year. He reached the 25-goal (28) and 50-point (50) plateaus for the fifth straight time, but he missed 17 contests due to a hand injury and his assist total decreased by nearly half (22 compared to 38). The fact Forsberg finished with just three power-play helpers in 64 games is nearly impossible to believe and has the look of a number that should regress positively going forward. Forsberg isn't a perfect player, and he's missed a minimum of 15 games in each of the past two seasons, but he is also a legitimate first-line sniper who is just now entering his prime at age 25. There's major breakout potential here if the talented Swede can make it through a full season unscathed.

The emergence of Calder Trophy winner Elias Pettersson as Vancouver's No. 1 center allowed Horvat to slide into the second-line role he is best suited for. He remained a fixture on the Canucks power play (18 points, 3:26) and finished the 2018-19 season with a career-best 27 goals and 61 points. Horvat has more natural skill than he gets credit for, but his biggest asset is his ability to contribute in all three zones. To give you an idea of how much Vancouver relies on Horvat, he averaged more ice time last season (20:50) than Tyler Seguin, Blake Wheeler, Jack Eichel, Sebastian Aho, Johnny Gaudreau, Nikita Kucherov and Artemi Panarin, just to name a few. His ceiling isn't particularly high, but Horvat is once again primed for 60-65 points, which make him worthy of a mid-round pick.

Jones posted by far the worst statistical season of his career with a 2.94 GAA and .896 save percentage in 2018-19, but he still managed to win 36 games for a powerhouse Sharks team. San Jose is loaded up for another run, so Jones could be one of the best fantasy goalies in the league if he reverts back to his career 2.47 GAA and .912 save marks. Even if he can't find his game, Jones should remain a strong source of wins as long as he holds onto the starting job. Backup Aaron Dell made only 20 starts and posted a 3.17 GAA last season, so he doesn't seem like an imminent threat to the starter's workload.

After missing Montreal's first 24 contests last season due to a knee injury, Weber played in every game for the Habs the rest of the way. The owner of arguably the best slap shot in the league, Weber should continue racking up goals if he remains healthy after a 14-goal, 33-point showing last year. His power-play production was uncharacteristically mediocre (five goals, six points) in 2018-19, but those numbers should return to the mean over time. Now 34 years old, Weber's body could keep wearing down, but there's a boatload of fantasy potential here if he can somehow make it through another season in one piece.

Gallagher finished with a career-high 33 goals in 2018-19 despite scoring just three times in his final 15 contests. He also played in all 82 games for a second straight season. Gallagher is a good player, but there are reasons for pessimism moving forward. First off, he never contributes much in the assist category (19 last season), which depresses his point total. Secondly, outside of a fluky 2017-18 season in which he posted 17 points with the man advantage, Gallagher has never been much of a threat on the power play despite receiving significant time (2:27 in each of the past two seasons) with his team up a man. The 27-year-old provides additional value in leagues that value goals more significantly than helpers, but fantasy owners expecting 35-plus markers again this season are likely to be disappointed.

Van Riemsdyk's first season back in Philadelphia was inconsistent. His overall numbers (27 goals, 48 points in 66 games) were respectable, but they were also considerably worse than his final two years in Toronto and certainly not what they Flyers were expecting when they handed JVR a five-year, $35 million contract in July 2018. Simply put, van Riemsdyk needs to shoot the puck more. He averaged just 2.53 shots on goal per game last season compared to 3.06 in 2017-18. JVR is expected to begin this upcoming season on Philadelphia's second line alongside Jake Voracek and newcomer Kevin Hayes. It's a unit with the potential to do serious offensive damage, and that, combined with van Riemsdyk's secure role on the Flyers power-play, makes him worthy of a mid-round selection in fantasy drafts.

Karlsson's 43-goal breakout in 2017-18 was the result of an unsustainable 23.4 (!) shooting percentage, and unsurprisingly, his goal total dropped to 24 last year as he reverted to a much more manageable mark of 14.2. That's the bad news. The good news is that Karlsson remained one of the Golden Knights' most productive players (56 points in 82 games) and has fit in exceptionally well on the top line alongside Jonathan Marchessault and Reilly Smith. All told, the 26-year-old Swede should be primed for another big season in Sin City. Just don't expect 40 goals.

Zucker remains on the Minnesota roster after multiple trades reportedly fell through, and he will look to rebound after a 2018-19 season that featured depressed numbers (21 goals, 21 assists, 42 points) across the board. Zucker was still effective with the man advantage (seven goals, 14 points), but that number shows just how unreliable he was at even strength. Zucker is theoretically a rebound candidate. After all, this is a player who posted 33 goals and 64 points as recently as two seasons ago, but he is almost certainly still on the trade block in Minnesota, and the whole set of circumstances creates an awkward situation for the team, player and, by extension, prospective fantasy owners.

Korpisalo will have some massive shoes to fill in Columbus this season with Sergei Bobrovsky having taken his talents as close to South Beach as you can get in the NHL. The Finnish netminder gave Blue Jackets fans plenty to be excited about with a 2.60 GAA and .920 save percentage over 31 games as a rookie back in 2015-16, but he's been unable to rediscover that form since. Korpisalo will be thrown into the fire with nobody but Latvian prospect Elvis Merzlikins on hand to pick up the slack should he struggle, but Columbus' faith in the 2012 third-rounder could be misplaced considering he's posted an .897 save percentage in each of the past two seasons.
