The departure of John Tavares to the Maple Leafs as an unrestricted free agent in the summer of 2018 forced the Islanders to spread the offensive wealth around, and while the team took a step forward in 2018-19, Barzal's personal numbers took a major hit. The former NHL Rookie of the Year finished with 23 less points (62) than his stellar freshman campaign. Barzal was moved off New York's top power-play unit late in the season and into the playoffs. The 22-year-old is one of the most gifted one-on-one players in the NHL, but his awareness in his own zone has failed to improve and head coach Barry Trotz isn't one to ignore defensive shortcomings. Barzal remains the most dangerous weapon in the Islanders' lineup and a quality rebound candidate, but fantasy owners can't be banking on 80-plus points once again.

After a dominant three-year stretch in which Holtby won 40-plus games with a GAA no worse than 2.22, he declined to 34 wins and a 2.99 GAA in 2017-18 followed by 32 and 2.82 last season. Those drafting Holtby in hopes of a return to that previous dominance are likely to be left disappointed, but there's still plenty of value to be found in the workhorse netminder considering the Capitals have made the playoffs in each of the past five seasons and 11 of the last 12.

Fantasy owners caught a break when Malkin managed to suit up for 78 games two seasons ago, but the Russian superstar again battled injuries in 2018-19. A pair of upper-body issues (combined with a one-game suspension) ended up costing Malkin 14 contests worth of action. He was exceedingly productive (72 points in 68 games), but the 33-year-old has reached the 70-game plateau just once in the past six seasons. There's comfort in knowing Malkin is all but a lock for a point-per-game when healthy, but he's getting up there in age and these nagging injuries are likely to take even longer to heal, moving forward.

Bishop is coming off the best season of his career in terms of both GAA (1.98) and save percentage (.934), though a lower-body injury limited him to only 46 appearances. A clean bill of health would result in more playing time this season, which would help offset any decline in Bishop's rate stats. With a career 2.30 GAA and .921 save percentage, coupled with a competitive veteran team in front of him that now boasts Joe Pavelski and Corey Perry, there's a lot to like about the 6-foot-7 netminder.

Connor continues to make his mark as one of the game's most prolific snipers. He is fresh off a season in which he set a new career high in goals (34) and shattered his previous bests in points (66), shots on goal (227), power-play points (19), and ice time (19:15). Connor offers stunningly little by way of secondary statistics  -- he had just 18 PIM and nine hits in 82 games last season -- but fantasy owners couldn't care less if he continues to put the puck in the net. Set to line up once again alongside Blake Wheeler and Mark Scheifele on one of the NHL's most dominant lines, as long as the restricted free agent and the Jets get a deal done before the season starts (he’s unsigned as of late September), Connor is worth an early investment across all fantasy formats.

In the midst of what is expected to be a prolonged rebuild, Larkin is the only Detroit player worth betting on from a fantasy standpoint. Outside of a minor neck ailment which cost him five games in March, Larkin remained healthy for a fourth straight season. His 32 goals and 76 points were career-best marks by a significant margin. He also racked up 15 points with the man advantage after mustering just 20 total power-play points in his first three NHL campaigns combined. Larkin has a world of talent and is clearly going to play a ton, so his numbers don't figure to decline much, but betting on one of the few talented offensive players on one of the league's shallowest teams is a risky proposition. Fantasy owners expecting Larkin to take another step forward are setting themselves up for disappointment.

The addition of former two-time Norris Trophy winner Erik Karlsson San Jose didn't slow down the production of Burns. In fact, Burns averaged over a point-per-game (83 in 82) for the first time in his career while again finishing as the runaway league leader in defensemen scoring. Also, Burns' 300 shots on goal placed him seventh overall in the NHL, while the next closest defenseman on the list (Nashville's Roman Josi) finished with 274. A former forward, the ability of Burns to create offense from the back end makes him one of the NHL's most dangerous weapons. Burns hasn't missed a game in five seasons and his lowest point total in that time was 60 back in 2014-15. Burns will be 35 years old by the conclusion of the 2019-20 campaign, but he has displayed no signs of slowing down.

Remember the first half of the 2018-19 season when St. Louis was dead last in the NHL and fans were clamoring for Tarasenko to be traded? The Russian forward found his game in the second half of the year and into the playoffs, helping the Blues to their first ever Stanley Cup. Tarasenko has scored 33 goals in back-to-back seasons after posting 40 and 39 tallies in 2015-16 and 2016-17 respectively, but his power-play production (12 goals, 22 points) remains as strong as ever, and he's always been durable. Tarasenko may not develop into the 50-goal man some expected, but he is a lock for 30-plus goals and 65-plus points if he remains healthy. Also, it's worth noting that the 27-year-old underwent arthroscopic shoulder surgery following St. Louis' postseason run but should be ready to roll for training camp.

Kakko is one of the most physically prepared teenage specimens to enter the league in quite some time after being selected second overall by the Rangers in June. The big Finn won World Junior gold and a senior Men's World Championship gold medal in the past 12 months to go along with setting a new Finnish league record for most goals (22 in 45 games last season) by an under-18 player. Kakko is set to begin this coming year in a top-six role on Broadway, and his size and strength should allow him to be an immediate contributor for the Rangers.

Murray rightfully has a reputation for being injury-prone, but he's actually maintained a stable workload with either 49 or 50 appearances in each of the past three seasons. The 25-year-old has won between 27 and 32 games in each of those seasons, and his 2.69 GAA and .919 save percentage in 2018-19 were right in line with his career 2.62 and .917 marks. After some early-career postseason heroics, Murray seems to have stabilized as a good but not elite goalie. Unlike some of his earlier seasons, the Thunder Bay native is unlikely to cruise to many victories on an aging Pittsburgh team that's fighting to keep its window open.

Already mentioned as one of the early favorites for the Calder Trophy, Makar's fantasy stock rose after Colorado shipped power-play quarterback Tyson Barrie to Toronto in July. The 20-year-old showed the Avs more than enough in a brief 10-game postseason stint (one goal, six points) to make the organization feel comfortable turning the reigns over to him as the team's top offensive blueliner. Makar's elusiveness and acceleration are remarkable for such a young kid, and while there will undoubtedly be bumps in the road, he has the look of a future superstar that should pile up the points for fantasy owners as he continues to adjust to life on hockey's biggest stage.

Hampered by a hand injury that required surgery and cost him a month's worth of action from early December to right after New Year's, Mantha's 2018-19 campaign was on the verge of being deemed a disappointment before he exploded for eight goals and 15 points in his final eight games, including a five-point outing in late March. His final numbers (25 goals, 48 points, 13 power-play points) were virtually identical to his output from the year prior, which suggests he's established a floor fantasy owners can depend on. Offensively, Mantha has it all. However, the 6-foot-4 Quebec native plays for one of the least-talented teams in the league and doesn't have much help outside of Dylan Larkin, so don't overpay on draft day.

Fantasy owners around the world invested in Ehlers last fall and got burned for it. After playing all 82 games the prior two seasons, a lingering upper-body injury cost the 23-year-old 20 games worth of action from early in the new year, and he posted just 10 points in 22 games after returning. In Ehlers' defense, he was playing with a broken foot in the postseason. He's scheduled to be fully healthy for training camp, and fantasy owners would be wise to pounce on Ehlers come draft day if he's available at a discount. The Jets remain a strong team, and it's not as if Ehlers, who posted back-to-back 60-plus point seasons in 2016-17 and 2017-18 and is yet to enter the prime of his career, suddenly forgot how to play hockey. There's major bounce-back appeal here.

The fact that Keller was one of fantasy hockey’s biggest disappointments in 2018-19 didn’t stop Arizona from resigning him to an eight-year, $57.2 million extension in September. His numbers dropped across the board (14 goals, 47 points) compared to his stellar rookie campaign (23 goals, 65 points), and he managed to post a minus-21 rating despite playing for a team that greatly overachieved. His poor season aside, there are reasons to be optimistic about the 2016 seventh-overall selection. First, he’s durable: Keller hasn’t missed a game in his first two NHL seasons. Also, his production with the man advantage (19 points last season) remains exceptional. Keller is such a talented offensive player that 50 points should be considered his floor, and those who can snatch him up at a discount in their drafts should be all over it given the looming bounce-back scenario in 2019-20.

Dallas reportedly refused to include Heiskanen in a potential deal with Ottawa for Erik Karlsson not all that long ago, and now one season into Heiskanen's NHL career, it's easy to see why. The 2017 third-overall pick was everything Dallas could have hoped for and more in his first go-around, leading all rookie defensemen in goals (12), shots (182), and average ice time (23:07), and finished second in scoring (33 points) to Buffalo's Rasmus Dahlin. The presence of John Klingberg will force Heiskanen to the second power-play unit in Big D, but he's so dependable in all situations that his production shouldn't suffer as a result. Expect the 20-year-old Finn to easily crack the 40-point plateau in his second NHL season.

Hutton posted a stellar 2.09 GAA and .931 save percentage in 32 appearances with the Blues in 2017-18, but those numbers had more to do with playing behind an elite defense that helped the team bring home the Stanley Cup a year after his departure. Meanwhile, Hutton parlayed that campaign into a contract with Buffalo, where he became a starter for the first time. Things went about as expected for a guy who had never previously cracked 40 appearances in a season since making it to the NHL in 2013 -- Hutton won just 18 times in 48 starts while posting a 3.00 GAA and .908 save percentage. The Sabres are hoping to flip the switch to contention behind a timeshare of Hutton and Linus Ullmark, but it's best to remain skeptical given the Sabres' track record of futility.

With Artemi Panarin leaving for the Rangers and Matt Duchene off to Nashville, Dubois will be counted on to help lead the offensive attack for the Jackets moving forward, and if the 2018-19 season was any indication, it's appears he'll be up to the task. Dubois is coming off a campaign in which he posted career highs (27 goals, 34 assists, 61 points) across the board as a 20-year-old. Sure, Columbus' offensive depth has taken a hit, but Dubois will be expected to shoulder an even bigger load on the power play, and that's good news for fantasy owners. Those looking for a steady, durable (Dubois hasn't missed a game in his first two NHL seasons) upside play should strongly consider him.

Buffalo missed the playoffs (again) in 2018-19, but the emergence of Dahlin as a legitimate top-pairing defenseman at age 18 was undoubtedly the brightest spot in what was another rough season for the Sabres. Dahlin posted just five points in his first 16 NHL games, but he got progressively stronger as the year went on and finished with a streak of seven points in his final 11 contests. The fact Dahlin was able to play 82 effective games at such a young age bodes extremely well for his future. He led all rookie defenseman in assists (35) and points (44) while finishing second in goals (nine) and average ice time (21:09). Look for Dahlin to take on an even more substantial role as he continues to mature and acclimate to life in the NHL, which should translate to increased production in upstate New York for the youngster.

The  hockey world knows Kucherov is a superstar, but what he did last season was truly spectacular. The runaway winner of the Hart Memorial Trophy as NHL MVP, Kucherov is coming off a season in which he led the league in points (128), assists (87) and power-play points (48). His 128 points and 87 assists were each 12 more than Connor McDavid. He scored more goals last year (41) than two seasons ago (39) despite finishing with 33 fewer shots. Tampa Bay remains the NHL's most talented team, and Kucherov is somehow just 26 years of age, so more elite production is likely on the way for No. 86.

Letang is coming off one of the most productive offensive seasons of his career (16 goals, 56 points in 65 games) despite missing 17 contests worth of action, mostly due to a nagging upper-body injury. The 32-year old finds a way to produce when healthy, but this is a player who has managed to play more than 71 games just once in the past eight seasons. The return of Justin Schultz to full health following a season in which he missed 53 games further complicates things. Letang's massive upside makes him a worthy dice-roll in the fantasy realm, but owners considering building their blue line around him should be very cautious of the potential injury concerns.

The proud owner of back-to-back 91-point seasons, Wheeler has firmly established himself as one of the NHL's premier offensive players. He is a beast with the man advantage (33 points in 2018-19) and serves as one of Winnipeg's key contributors in all situations. Having missed just one regular-season game in the past four seasons, Wheeler also has durability on his side. The Jets are going to score a ton of goals again this coming year and the American will certainly be right in the middle of it. The 33-year-old may not be as attractive a fantasy selection as players like Connor McDavid and Nikita Kucherov, but his numbers figure to be in the same ballpark with those guys when all is said and done this season.

Rask has arguably the highest floor at the goaltending position. His GAA hasn't climbed higher than 2.56 in any of the past eight seasons, and a Boston team that came one game from claiming the Stanley Cup last season is capable of bailing Rask out when he has a rare off-night. A concussion limited the Finnish netminder to 46 appearances and 27 wins in 2018-19, but he figures to bounce back in those categories after topping 30 wins and 50 starts in each of the previous five campaigns. At 32 years old, age-related decline also isn't a major concern yet, as goalies tend to have significantly longer primes than skaters.

Although Giordano has been one of the NHL's better defensemen for more than half a decade, not many could have foreseen his shocking 2018-19 Norris Trophy-winning campaign. He ranked third among all blueliners in both goals (17) and assists (57) while landing second in points (74). On the surface, this sudden increase in production seems anomalous, but take a deeper dive and Giordano's breakout production actually seems somewhat sustainable. His shot total (221), shooting percentage (7.7), ice time (24:14) and power-play time (3:19) were all roughly in line with Giordano's averages over the past four years. While he is unlikely to score 17 goals again and his assist total figures to dip some, Giordano should remain one of the NHL's best offensive blueliners, especially given that Calgary's "big four" up front in Johnny Gaudreau, Sean Monahan, Elias Lindholm and Matthew Tkachuk are all returning and either in, or approaching  their prime.

While Giroux didn't come close last season to matching the whopping 102 points he posted two years ago, the 2018-19 campaign still went down as one of the better seasons of Giroux's 12-year NHL career. He averaged more than a point per game (85 in 82) while once again producing amply (23 points) with the man advantage. Giroux's 2017-18 breakout was the result of a bloated 17.6 shooting percentage, which is a number that dropped to a far more reasonable 9.6 last year and is the main reason Giroux's goal total dropped from 34 to 22. The drop-off aside, the Flyers have a talented offensive supporting cast around Giroux, and given the fact he hasn't missed a game in the past three seasons, the 31-year-old should be good for another run at 80-plus points.

A big, strong two-way center, Scheifele has been at the forefront of Winnipeg's resurgence the past several seasons. The 26-year-old has averaged at least a point per game in each of the past three years and set a career-best mark with 84 points in 2018-19. A part of one of the NHL's most dominant lines with Blake Wheeler and Kyle Connor, Scheifele's numbers could very well increase this season. Assuming his power-play production (23 points) last year wasn't a mirage, Scheifele should threaten the 90-point plateau in 2019-20. He is a legitimate No. 1 fantasy center.

The first-overall selection in the 2019 draft, Hughes has been on the prospect radar for the past several years. He is the United States National Team Development Program's all-time leading scorer and is set to be the first player in program history to go straight from the USNTDP directly to the NHL. He is projected to fill a top-six role for the Devils immediately along with being a mainstay on their top power-play unit. Hughes is a dynamic all-around offensive talent that projects to be a franchise-altering asset. He's undersized (5-foot-10, 170 pounds) and could easily struggle with the rigors of professional hockey in the early going, but his natural ability is going to win out in the end. 50 points is a reasonable expectation for Hughes in his rookie campaign.

Viewed by many as a safe selection without a ton of upside when he was drafted sixth-overall by Calgary in 2013, Monahan finally had a true breakout season in 2018-19. He set a new career-high in goals with 34 and points with 82. Monahan's increased production was due to the fact he picked up 15 more assists last year than in 2017-18. The 24-year-old has posted no fewer than 17 power-play points in each of the past five seasons and has never played in fewer than 74 games in a single campaign in his six-year NHL career. Even if you still aren't a true believer in Monahan's long-term potential, the fact he centers superstar Johnny Gaudreau on a nightly basis is a plum assignment that should continue to translate to big things in the fantasy arena.

Werenski is coming off another productive season in Columbus, where his numbers (11 goals, 44 points in 82 games) were right in line with his career averages. Also, his time with the man advantage (2:27) was virtually identical to the year prior (2:26). It's important to note that Werenski shot the puck far less in 2018-19 (168 shots on goal) than 2017-18 (207), but the defections of Artemi Panarin to the Rangers and Matt Duchene to Nashville figure to result in Werenski getting the puck to the net more frequently in 2019-20. The presence of Seth Jones on the Columbus blue line somewhat limits Werenski's ceiling, but the 22-year-old retains one of the highest floors among fantasy rearguards.

Backlund has quietly developed into one of the NHL's most dependable assets. He has finished with no fewer than 45 points in each of the past four seasons and has reached the 20-goal plateau in three of the past four. Backlund's production is driven by his durability; he has missed just six regular season games since the start of the 2015-16 season. Backlund's 47-point 2018-19 season was made even more impressive by the fact he finished with just two (one goal, one assist) power-play points after his time with the man advantage dropped to 1:39 compared to 2:08 two years ago. Owners looking for some offensive punch on the end of their fantasy bench could do worse thank giving the 30-year-old Swede a look.

Ekholm is coming off a season in which his career-best 44 points and plus-27 rating undoubtedly helped countless unsuspecting owners to a fantasy championship. The plus/minus could be sustainable moving forward given the well-roundedness of Nashville's lineup, but it's highly unlikely Ekholm will register 36 assists again this coming year due to his receiving little time with the man advantage (1:22 last season) and the fact nearly the entirety of his production came early in the season. He posted 36 points in his first 47 contests and finished in a slump that featured just one goal and five points in his final 27 games. Ekholm logs a ton of ice time (23:22 last season) and plays for a good team, so his production won't come to a grinding halt, but there are far more attractive fantasy blue-line options.

Rittich posted an outstanding 27-9-5 record last season to help lead Calgary to the best record in the Western Conference, but his 2.61 GAA and .911 save percentage weren't enough to earn any postseason action, as Mike Smith presided over the team's entire first-round loss to the Avalanche. Smith is now in Edmonton, with the Flames having signed Cam Talbot to take his place. Rittich and Talbot figure to split time early in the year, though the Czech netminder could run away with the job if Talbot fails to bounce back from an awful 2018-19 campaign. Conversely, Rittich could also see his workload dwindle if he suffers any setbacks with the knee injury that bothered him in the latter half of last season.

Columbus was unable to keep Artemi Panarin from departing despite a massive last-minute offer, but the club pivoted nicely on July 1 and signed Nyquist to a reasonable four-year, $22 million contract. The 30-year-old posted a career-best 60 points in a 2018-19 season split between Detroit and San Jose. Nyquist isn't Panarin (or Matt Duchene, for that matter), but the Swede has posted no fewer than 40 points in each of the past six seasons and has missed just seven regular-season games over the past five years. Nyquist makes for an intriguing source of secondary fantasy scoring given his dependability and assurance of a top-six role with the Jackets.

Vasilevskiy should finish among the league-leaders in wins after notching 83 victories over the past two seasons, and he added a 2.40 GAA and .925 save percentage in 2018-19 en route to the Vezina Trophy. Despite a shaky postseason performance, the Lightning handed Vasilevskiy an eight-year, $76 million extension, cementing him as the starting netminder for what should continue to be a dominant regular-season team. The 25-year-old Russian will likely come back down to earth after what could end up being the best season of his career, but there's still a strong case to be made for taking him as the first goalie off the board given his ideal surroundings.

Having quickly and deservedly developed a reputation as one of the NHL's premier snipers, Pastrnak is coming off a season in which he finished with a career-high 38 goals despite missing five weeks worth of action due to a thumb injury. Always among the league leaders in shots on goal, Pastrnak's ability to put the puck in the net along with his elite production with the man advantage (33 points in 2018-19) make the 23-year-old one of fantasy hockey's best options regardless of format. Given his continued growth and lofty offensive totals, don't be surprised if the Czech flirts with the 50-goal mark if he's able to stay healthy.

Seguin has produced no fewer than 26 goals and 72 points in each of his first six years with Dallas. Last season (33 goals, 80 points in 82 games) was one of Seguin's best to date, and he finished fourth in the league in shots on goal (334) after finishing second (335) in 2017-18. Seguin's new-found willingness to consistently get the puck toward the goal combined with Dallas' offensive depth and his production with the man advantage (no fewer than 24 points in each of the past six seasons) give Seguin both a high floor and high ceiling. Go ahead and make him your No. 1 fantasy center. He's worth it.

Landeskog has always been a solid player, but it's no coincidence that his sudden increase in production has coincided with the emergence of Nathan MacKinnon and Mikko Rantanen as legitimate NHL stars. Buoyed by a career-high 27 points with the man advantage, Landeskog finished the 2018-19 campaign with new bests in goals (34), assists (41), and points (75). The Swede's numbers would have been even better had he not missed nine games in March due to an upper-body injury. There's reason to believe the Avs' captain could be in for another big season, but Landeskog finished with 33 points as recently as 2016-17, and it's likely his point total would drop if the team lost either MacKinnon or Rantanen for an extended period.

It might not have been the standout freshman campaign many were hoping for, but the fact Svechnikov managed to finish his rookie season with 20 goals despite playing nearly the entire year as an 18-year-old is impressive. The second-overall pick in 2018, Svechnikov played in all 82 regular-season games before a concussion suffered in a fight with Washington's Alex Ovechkin caused him to miss six postseason contests. Fantasy owners looking for an immediate and potentially massive increase in offensive production should be targeting the talented Russian. He's big (6-foot-2, 195 pounds), strong and willing to go to the difficult areas of the ice to make a play. Savvy dynasty-league owners would be wise to throw out a low-ball offer for Svechnikov and see if they can nab him at a discount.

A severe groin injury cost Karlsson 27 of San Jose's final 32 regular-season games. He managed to return for the first 19 of the Sharks' 20-game postseason run, but he was clearly hampered and compensating for the injury. Karlsson was scheduled to become an unrestricted free agent on July 1, but the Sharks clearly felt comfortable enough to offer the Swede an eight-year, $92 million contract in June. Karlsson underwent surgery for the groin issue this offseason and is expected to be ready for training camp with said extension in hand. The former Senator was productive when healthy (45 points in 53 games) in his first year with Team Teal, but what fantasy owners will get from Karlsson moving forward is anyone's guess.

Stamkos is coming off his fifth 40-goal season, his fourth 90-point season, and his second 40 power play point season in his illustious career. While his 19.2 percent shooting percentage was abnormally high, he has always been a guy who takes full advantage of his offensive opportunities, and even a slight dip in production would make Stamkos worthy of a late first-round pick. With the Lightning set to reign as one of the NHL's top clubs once again and defending league MVP Nikita Kucherov entrenched next to Stammer on Tampa's top line, don't expect the 29-year-old's offensive production to drop off all that much in 2019-20.

The Caps caught a lot of flack for signing Carlson to an eight-year, $64 million contract in June 2018, but the 29-year-old defender earned his money and then some last season with a career-high 70 points. The setup man on Washington's deadly power-play, Carlson finished with a career-best 33 points with the man advantage while racking up an eye-popping 4:05 worth of power-play ice time per game. In other words, Carlson is seemingly always out there whenever Washington is up a man. Carlson was a nice player early in his career, but he has taken his game to a new level the past two seasons. Set to play upwards of 25 minutes per game  and with his role as Washington's number-one defenseman on lockdown, Carlson is primed for another massive fantasy campaign in 2019-20.

Constantly mentioned in trade rumors for the past few years, the Penguins finally dealt Kessel to Arizona in June. The 2017-18 campaign (82 points) marked the second straight season the forward has averaged a point per game. His production with the man advantage stayed elite (12 goals, 36 points), and Kessel played in 82 regular season games for a sixth straight season. Arizona doesn't have the high-end offensive talent on its roster that Pittsburgh possesses, but Kessel's sniping ways should be a good fit alongside playmakers Clayton Keller, Nick Schmaltz, and Derek Stepan. Given his durability and secure role as Arizona's top goal-scoring threat, a return to the 80-point plateau should be within reach for the Wisconsin native.

It was another productive offensive season for Klingberg (10 goals, 45 points in 64 games) despite the fact he underwent hand surgery in mid-November, which cost him five weeks worth of action. The emergence of rookie stud Miro Heiskanen allowed the Stars to scale back Klingberg's time with the man advantage by an average of 40 seconds (2:59), though his overall ice time (24:32) was the highest of his five-year NHL career. Klingberg isn't Erik Karlsson or Brent Burns, but he's one of the NHL's very best offensive defenseman and has never posted a negative plus/minus rating in his entire career. Invest in the 27-year-old with confidence.

Mrazek emerged as Carolina's No. 1 goalie last season, notching 23 wins with a 2.39 GAA and . 914 save percentage in 40 regular-season starts before leading the team to the Eastern Conference finals. After signing a two-year extension in the offseason, he'll open as the starter on a young team looking to build off last season's success. It's not all sunshine and rainbows for Mrazek, however, as the Czech netminder recorded a career-best 27 wins and 2.33 GAA for Detroit in 2015-16, only to watch his GAA balloon to over 3.00 in each of the next two seasons. Should he slip up, James Reimer and 2018-19 AHL goalie of the year Alex Nedeljkovic will be waiting in the wings to usurp Mrazek, but Carolina's deep defense corps should help Mrazek get off to a quick start and strengthen his grip on the starting spot.

Pacioretty's first season in Vegas was a disappointment. He missed 16 games due to a variety of injuries and wasn't all that productive (22 goals in 66 games) when healthy. His production (four goals, eight points) with the man advantage dropped considerably from his final seasons in Montreal, and so the glass-half-full take would be that Max was just getting used to playing in his new surroundings and the rigors of Western Conference hockey. On the other hand, Pacioretty turns 31 in November and has been banged up two seasons in a row. His role in Vegas' top six is probably secure, but he needs a bounce-back effort to restore the confidence of fantasy owners.

Although Barrie had been on the trade block for quite a while, few saw Toronto as his ultimate destination. The move became official on July 1 when a package headlined by Nazem Kadri was shipped to Colorado in exchange for the services of Barrie and forward Alex Kerfoot. With the Leafs struggling for cap space and Barrie set to become an unrestricted free agent in the summer of 2020, there's a real chance he could end up serving as a one-year rental for Toronto. The 28-year-old power-play specialist has posted no fewer than 14 goals and 57 points (including 25 with the man advantage) over the past two seasons and is a perfect fit for Toronto's top power-play unit alongside lefty Morgan Rielly. Ultimately, Barrie traded one talented supporting cast in Colorado for another with the Leafs, and his production should remain steady in his new home.

Fantasy owners who drafted Voracek last season in hopes of a return to 85-point land year ended up getting burned. The 30-year-old finished 19 points off that pace, thanks largely in part to his power-play production returning to normal. Voracek posted 18 points with the man advantage compared to 35 two seasons ago, and that difference alone almost covers his entire drop in scoring. His numbers last season (20 goals, 66 points) were much more in line with his career averages and give us a baseline with regards to what to expect moving forward. Sure, Voracek could have another big year if some bounces go his way for an extended period (it's happened twice before), but fantasy owners need to view another potential monster season as an exception rather than the rule.

One of the most consistent players in the league, Couture took his game to a new level during San Jose's 20-game 2018-19 postseason run. He finished with 14 goals and 20 points in those 20 games and was seemingly making a huge game-changing play every night. Couture is an ideal second-line pivot. He's talented offensively, aware defensively and makes plays with the man advantage. His sparkling playoff run aside, Couture is yet to have a true breakout season. He has never posted fewer than 23 goals and 52 points in a year in which he has played at least 65 games, but his career high in points (posted last season) is just 70. The 30-year-old makes for a nice addition to any fantasy squad, but don't overpay on draft day for a jump in regular-season production that is unlikely to materialize, especially after the departure of captain Joe Pavelski.

Struggling to find his footing as an NHL player and in desperate need of a change of scenery, Strome found new life following a late November trade to Chicago. He finished with 51 points in 58 games with his new club and settled in very nicely as the Hawks' second-line center behind Jonathan Toews. Strome's lack of foot speed is an issue, but he is an underrated playmaker and displays terrific offensive instincts. Chicago has enough depth on the wing to ensure Strome lines up alongside a pair of talented offensive players, and his role with the man advantage (3:00 on average) should be secure. It's entirely possible what we saw from Strome last season is his ultimate ceiling, but in case there's still some untapped potential, it wouldn't hurt to take a flier on him if he slips far enough in drafts.
